│     └──────────────────────────────────────┘            │
│                                                         │
│   Governing Variables: [κ] ──► [κ] (unchanged)         │
│   Z-State: :maintenance — preserving equilibrium        │
│   Element: Earth/δγ (cycling within pattern)            │
│                                                         │
│   Like a thermostat: "Room cold → Heat on → Check"     │
│                                                         │
└─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┘

DOUBLE-LOOP (Air-dominant transformation)
┌─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┐
│                                                         │
│   Error ──[σ]──► Question ──[σ+δγ]──► Transform        │
│     │              Assumptions      Governing          │
│     │                  │            Variables          │
│     │                  ▼                 │              │
│     │            ┌───────────┐           │              │
│     │            │  NEW      │◄──────────┘              │
│     │            │ASSUMPTIONS│                          │
│     │            │  [β]      │                          │
│     │            └─────┬─────┘                          │
│     │                  │                                │
│     └──────────────────┘                                │
│                                                         │
│   Governing Variables: [κ₁] ──► [κ₂] (transformed)     │
│   Z-State: :transformative — new equilibrium            │
│   Element: Air/σ (surfacing) + Earth/δγ (processing)    │
│                                                         │
│   Like a thermostat asking: "Why 72°F?"                │
│                                                         │
└─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┘
```

## Espoused vs. Theory-in-Use as NEMEtic Gap

```
┌─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┐
│                                                         │
│   The Gap is ε made visible                             │
│                                                         │
│   ESPoused THEORY ─────────────────────►               │
│   [What we say we believe]                              │
│        │                                                │
│        │  This gap is defended                          │
│        │  because it protects us from:                 │
│        │  • Anxiety (Water/ρ↓)                         │
│        │  • Loss of control (Fire/λ↓)                  │
│        │  • Vulnerability (Water/ρ↓)                   │
│        │                                                │
│        ▼                                                │
│   THEORY-IN-USE ───────────────────────►               │
│   [What our actions reveal]                             │
│        │                                                │
│        └── Often invisible to us (Air/σ↓)              │
│            visible to others                            │
│                                                         │
│   Double-loop learning requires:                        │
│   1. Making the gap visible (Air/σ↑)                    │
│   2. Tolerating the anxiety (Water/ρ↑)                  │
│   3. Inquiring with courage (Fire/λ↑)                   │
│   4. Transforming the pattern (Wood/β↑)                 │
│                                                         │
└─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┘
```

## Model I vs. Model II as Elemental Shift

| Dimension | Model I (Defensive) | Model II (Productive) |
|-----------|---------------------|----------------------|
| **Governing Variable** | Win, control, suppress feelings | Valid info, free choice, commitment |
| **Elemental Pattern** | Fire/λ↑ + Metal/μ↑ (control) | Air/σ↑ + Water/ρ↑ (clarity + trust) |
| **Z-State** | :defensive | :transformative |
| **Learning Capacity** | Single-loop only | Double-loop enabled |
| **Relational Quality** | Low trust (Water/ρ↓) | High trust (Water/ρ↑) |

## Key NEMEtic Insight

> Double-Loop Learning is the practice of **assumption archaeology** — the disciplined excavation of the beliefs that govern our actions. Most learning stays at the surface (single-loop) because going deeper threatens our defensive routines. The Air/σ capacity to distinguish assumptions from reality, combined with the Earth/δγ capacity to reflect deeply, creates the conditions for genuine transformation. But this requires Fire/λ courage and Water/ρ safety — we will not expose our governing variables unless we feel secure enough to be vulnerable. The genius of Argyris and Schön is showing that organizational learning is not about better information but about **lower defenses**.

## Diagnostic Questions for Double-Loop Learning

| Question | Element | Purpose |
|----------|---------|---------|
| "What am I assuming that leads me to act this way?" | σ | Surface governing variables |
| "How did I come to believe this?" | δγ | Trace assumption history |
| "What would I do if I weren't afraid?" | λ + ρ | Reveal defensive routines |
| "What am I protecting by not changing?" | ρ | Surface emotional stakes |
| "What alternative assumptions are possible?" | β | Generate new frames |
| "How can we test these assumptions together?" | μ + σ | Public inquiry |

## ε Preservation Protocol

To maintain the productive incompleteness of Double-Loop Learning:

1. **Never claim full access** — We can never fully know our theory-in-use
2. **Stay in inquiry** — Advocacy closes; questions open
3. **Test publicly** — Assumptions held alone become rigid
4. **Tolerate anxiety** — Defensive arousal is information, not error
5. **Honor the gap** — The space between espoused and enacted is where learning lives

